1
2 BE IT ENACTED BY THE PEOPLE OF THE STATE OF OKLAHOMA:
3 SECTION 1. NEW LAW A new section of law not to be
4 codified in the Oklahoma Statutes reads as follows:
5 This act shall be known and may be cited as the "Blake Burgess
6 Act".
7 SECTION 2. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
8 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 1-630 of Title 63, unless there
9 is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
10 Each hospital with an emergency department and each ambulatory
11 surgical center shall:
12 1. Develop and implement policies and procedures for the
13 rendering of appropriate medical attention for persons at risk of
14 forming venous thromboembolisms which reflect evidence-based best
15 practices relating to, at a minimum:
16 a. assessing patients for risk of venous thromboembolism
17 using a nationally recognized risk assessment tool,
18 and
19 b. treatment options for a patient diagnosed with venous
20 thromboembolism; and
21 2. Train all nonphysician personnel at least annually on the
22 policies and procedures developed under this section. For purposes
23 of this section, the term "nonphysician personnel" means all
24 personnel of the licensed facility working in clinical areas and
Req. No. 16870 Page 2

1 prov iding patient care, except those persons licensed as health care
2 practitioners. In no case shall this be construed to require
3 personnel to practice outside the scope of his or her certification,
4 license, or qualification.
5 SECTION 3. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
6 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 1-631 of Title 63, unless there
7 is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
8 A. The State Department of Health shall contract with the
9 state-designated health information exchange to establish and
10 maintain a statewide venous thromboembolism registry to ensure that
11 the performance measures required to be submitted under subsection B
12 of this section are maintained and available for use to improve or
13 modify the venous thromboembolism care system, ensure compliance
14 with nationally recognized guidelines, and monitor venous
15 thromboembolism patient outcomes.
16 B. Beginning July 1, 2027, each hospital with an emergency
17 department shall annually report to the statewide venous
18 thromboembolism registry information containing nationally
19 recognized venous thromboembolism measures and data on the incidence
20 and prevalence of venous thromboembolisms. Such data shall include
21 the following information:
22 1. The number of venous thromboembolisms identified and
23 diagnosed;
24 2. The age of the patient;
Req. No. 16870 Page 3

1 3. The ZIP code of the patient;
2 4. The sex of the patient;
3 5. Whether the patient is a resident of a licensed nursing or
4 assisted living facility;
5 6. Whether the venous thromboembolism was fatal;
6 7. How the diagnosis was made, such as by using imaging
7 modalities; and
8 8. The treatment that was recommended for the venous
9 thromboembolism.
10 C. The Department shall require the state-designated health
11 information exchange to collect data from each hospital with an
12 emergency department on the performance measures required under
13 subsection B of this section. The state-designated health
14 information exchange shall provide to the Department regular reports
15 on the data collected.
16 D. By June 1, 2027, the Department shall submit to the
17 Governor, the President Pro Tempore of the Oklahoma State Senate,
18 and the Speaker of the Oklahoma House of Representatives a detailed
19 report on incidents of venous thromboembolism using inpatient and
20 outpatient data for services provided between July 1, 2026, and June
21 30, 2027. The report shall provide analyses of all of the
22 following:
23 1. Age category, initial primary diagnosis and procedure, and
24 secondary diagnoses, readmission rates for inpatients, admission
Req. No. 16870 Page 4

1 rate s for venous thromboembolism for which the patient had an
2 ambulatory surgery procedure, and emergency department visits for
3 venous thromboembolism linked to any previous admission;
4 2. Whether the venous thromboembolism was present upon
5 admission;
6 3. The incidence of venous thromboembolism procedures reported
7 on the agency's website; and
8 4. The principal payor, the sex of the patient, and the
9 patient's discharge status.
10 E. The state-designated health information exchange operating
11 the registry shall only use or publish information from the registry
12 for the purposes of advancing medical research or medical education
13 in the interest of reducing morbidity or mortality.
14 SECTION 4. AMENDATORY 63 O.S. 2021, Section 1-890.2, is
15 amended to read as follows:
16 Section 1-890.2. As used in the Continuum of Care and Assisted
17 Living Act:
18 1. "Assisted living center" means any home or establishment
19 offering, coordinating or providing services to two or more persons
20 who:
21 a. are domiciled therein,
22 b. are unrelated to the operator,
23 c. by choice or functional impairments, need assistance
24 with personal care or nursing supervision,
Req. No. 16870 Page 5

1 d. may need intermittent or unscheduled nursing care,
2 e. may need medication assistance, and
3 f. may need assistance with transfer and/or ambulation;
4 2. "Board" means the State Board of Health;
5 3. "Commissioner" means the Commissioner of Health;
6 4. "Continuum of care facility" means a home, establishment or
7 institution providing nursing facility services as defined in
8 Section 1-1902 of this title and one or both of the following:
9 a. assisted living center services as defined in the
10 Continuum of Care and Assisted Living Act, and
11 b. adult day care center services as defined in Section
12 1-872 of this title; and
13 5. "Department" means the State Department of Health;
14 6. "Pulmonary embolism (PE)" means a condition in which part of
15 the clot breaks off and travels to the lungs, possibly causing
16 death; and
17 7. "Venous thromboembolism (VTE)" means deep vein thrombosis
18 (DVT), which is a blood clot located in a deep vein, usually in the
19 leg or arm. The term can be used to refer to DVT, pulmonary
20 embolism, or both.
21 SECTION 5. AMENDATORY 63 O.S. 2021, Section 1-890.3, as
22 amended by Section 1, Chapter 357, O.S.L. 2025 (63 O.S. Supp. 2025,
23 Section 1-890.3), is amended to read as follows:
24
Req. No. 16870 Page 6

1 Section 1-890.3. A. The State Commissioner of Health shall
2 promulgate rules necessary to implement the provisions of the
3 Continuum of Care and Assisted Living Act. Such rules shall
4 include, but shall not be limited to:
5 1. A uniform comprehensive resident screening instrument to
6 measure the needs and capabilities of residents in all settings and
7 to determine appropriate placements of residents. Such assessment
8 shall include recognizing the signs and symptoms of venous
9 thromboembolism (VTE) and techniques for providing an emergency
10 response;
11 2. Physical plant requirements meeting construction and life
12 safety codes, with provisions accommodating resident privacy and
13 independence in assisted living centers and in assisted living
14 components of continuum of care facilities based on the variable
15 capabilities of residents;
16 3. Staffing levels responsive to the variable needs of
17 residents, with provisions for sharing of staff between components
18 in a continuum of care facility;
19 4. Minimum standards for resident care including, but not
20 limited to, standards pertaining to medical care and administration
21 of medications. Standards pertaining to medication administration
22 shall, at a minimum, require the assisted living center or continuum
23 of care facility to:
24
Req. No. 16870 Page 7

1 a. provide or arrange qualified staff to administer
2 medications based on the needs of residents,
3 b. follow medication administration orders from a
4 qualified health care provider,
5 c. ensure that medications are reviewed monthly by a
6 Registered Nurse or pharmacist and quarterly by a
7 consultant pharmacist,
8 d. maintain medication administration records and
9 document all medication administration in such
10 records, and
11 e. have medication storage and disposal policies;
12 5. Standards for measuring quality outcomes for residents;
13 6. Provisions for individualized services chosen by and
14 designed for each resident;
15 7. Provisions to prohibit facility staff from disclosing a
16 resident’s financial information to third parties without written
17 consent of the resident or the designated representative of the
18 resident;
19 8. Procedures for inspections and investigations of licensed
20 entities to ensure compliance with the Continuum of Care and
21 Assisted Living Act and rules promulgated by the Commissioner;
22 9. Enumeration of resident rights and responsibilities to be
23 observed by each facility and its staff. Such resident rights shall
24 include the freedom of choice regarding any personal attending
Req. No. 16870 Page 8

1 phys icians and all other providers of medical services and supplies,
2 providing that the minimum standards are met by the provider
3 pursuant to the Continuum of Care and Assisted Living Act, without a
4 financial penalty or fee charged by the assisted living center;
5 10. Provisions for a surety bond or deposit from each applicant
6 in an amount sufficient to guarantee that obligations to residents
7 will be performed, with provisions for reduction or waiver of the
8 surety bond or deposit when the assets of the applicant or its
9 contracts with other persons are sufficient to reasonably ensure the
10 performance of its obligations;
11 11. Assisted living facilities shall provide a consumer
12 information pamphlet to residents upon admission. The pamphlet
13 shall contain information about venous thromboembolism (VTE), risk
14 factors, and how residents can recognize the signs and symptoms of
15 VTE. This shall be provided by the National Blood Clot Association
16 at no cost to the facility;
17 12. Provisions for the development of a consumer guide or
18 similar resource to be posted on the Internet website of the State
19 Department of Health to assist individuals and families in
20 understanding the services provided by assisted living centers and
21 to compare and select a facility;
22 12. 13. Provisions for posting results of routine inspections
23 and any complaint investigations of each assisted living center on
24 the Internet website of the Department. Such information shall be
Req. No. 16870 Page 9

1 regu larly updated to include the facility’s plan of correction and
2 to indicate when a violation of a licensing regulation was corrected
3 by the facility; and
4 13. 14. Provisions requiring execution of a plan of care and a
5 resident service contract with the resident or resident’s
6 representative.
7 B. The nursing care service of a continuum of care facility
8 shall be subject to the requirements, procedures and remedies set
9 out in the Nursing Home Care Act, including provisions relating to
10 resident rights.
11 C. The adult day care component of a continuum of care facility
12 shall be subject to requirements and procedures specified under the
13 Adult Day Care Act.
14 SECTION 6. This act shall become effective July 1, 2026.
15 SECTION 7. It being immediately necessary for the preservation
16 of the public peace, health or safety, an emergency is hereby
17 declared to exist, by reason whereof this act shall take effect and
18 be in full force from and after its passage and approval.
